    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-07-08T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-07-08T08:00:00-05:00" n="146"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d146">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">868.01/364: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador to the Greek Government in Exile</hi>
                        (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kirk</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-07-08T16:00:00+03:00"
                            >July 8, 1943—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received July 9—8:53 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Greek Series 17. Your Greek Series No. 5, July 5, 7 p.m. In reply to a letter to
                    Greek Prime Minister transmitting statement contained in the telegram under
                    reference, I have today received a communication from him as follows: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“The statement made by the Secretary of State Mr. Cordell Hull<note
                                n="27" xml:id="d146fn27">See <hi rend="italic">supra.</hi>
                            </note> on His Majesty’s radio to the Greek people was very gratifying
                            to us. It has indeed cast the proper light on this solemn and important
                            declaration of the sovereign which will undoubtedly have a decisive and
                            favorable influence on the solution of the political problems of our
                            country.</p>
                        <p>The Government and myself have also much appreciated the comments of
                            Senators Guffey and Pepper<note n="28" xml:id="d146fn28">Joseph F.
                                Guffey and Claude Pepper, Senators from Pennsylvania and Florida,
                                respectively.</note> on the same matter.</p>
                        <p>I should be grateful if you would kindly transmit to the Secretary of
                            State our sincere thanks for the warm reception which he and ether
                            distinguished American personalities gave to His Majesty’s speech thus
                            enlightening the public opinion of the United States on the significance
                            of this grave statement.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirk</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
